      • populateStore

        protected void populateStore​(edu.uiuc.ncsa.security.util.json.JSONStore store)
        Initialize the store. The entries are 
              {"#import":"id:array/1"} → ["A","B"]
      {"#import":"id:object/1"} → {"X":"x","Y","y"}
      {#import":"id:circular"} → {"A":"a","X":{"B":"b","#import":"id:circular"}}
        This gives a basic object and a basic array. The circular object is self-referential and there are tests that use it to show an exception is thrown when a cycle is found (or we get an infinite recursion.)
        Parameters:
        store -

      • testBasicObject

        public void testBasicObject()
                     throws Exception
        Show that an object of the form 
             {"Z":"z","#import":"id:object/1"}
        resolves to 
             {"Z":"z","X":"x","Y","y"}
        This shows that the resolution occurs at the same level as the import (this is important since we do not want this to nest things automatically.)
        Throws:
        Exception

      • testObjectNesting

        public void testObjectNesting()
                       throws Exception
        Tests that nesting of objects is resolved correctly. So 
           {"A":
     {"B":
        {"#import": "id:object/1"}
     }
  }
        resolves to 
           {"A":
     {"B":
       {"X": "x","Y": "y"}
     }
  }
        Throws:
        Exception

      • testArrayNesting

        public void testArrayNesting()
                      throws Exception
        Shows that an import nested inside arrays is resolved correctly. So 
             [[[{"#import": "id:array/1"}]]]
        resolves to 
            [[[
   "A","B"
 ]]]
        Note the level at which this is unpacked to be consistent: the elements of the array are placed at the same level where the import statement is rather than being turned into another array. This allows for overrides in arrays as well.
        Throws:
        Exception

      • testObjectOverride

        public void testObjectOverride()
                        throws Exception
        One of the most important features -- this allows for overriding values. This is accomplished by resolving the import at the correct level. The aim is that the value at the current level take precedence over the import. The stored object is {"X":"x","Y":"y"} and we need to show tjhat 
             {"X":"a","Z":"z","#import":"id:object/1"}
        resolves to 
            {"X":"a","Z":"z","Y":"y"}
        A final check shows that the import directive itself is removed.
        Throws:
        Exception

      • testArrayOverride

        public void testArrayOverride()
                       throws Exception
        the way arrays handle this is that, being lists, the redundant values are just added. In this case, 
             ["A","B",{"#import":"id:array/1"}
        resolves to 
             [A,B,A,B]
        Throws:
        Exception
